WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Please join me in welcoming Rob Hyndman.

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:23.120
Thank you. I'm Rob Hyndman. I'm a professor at Monash University in Australia, and I want

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:30.240
to take you to a land far, far away, Australia, to a time long, long ago when I looked more

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:39.439
like that. Actually, we don't need to go that far back. Maybe that far back. But actually,

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:47.560
I'm going to start about there. So I'm 17 there, so we're talking mid-80s, and I had

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:55.040
my first computer, so the first time I was ever trying to type a document on a computer.

00:00:55.799 --> 00:01:02.799
It looked a little bit like this. That's actually not my first word processor, but it was a

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:10.360
couple of years later. It was called WordStar 2000. I thought it was awesome. There's only

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.519
one other person in the room old enough to remember WordStar 2000. Unfortunately, they

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:23.519
went bust fairly quickly, so I switched to WordPerfect. A few more of them, which was

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:29.879
even more awesome because it was a markup language, and you had two sections of the

00:01:29.879 --> 00:01:34.559
screen. You could have WYSIWYG at the top, and down the bottom you had markup, and you

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:39.120
could see where bold was on and bold was off. I mean, even Microsoft Word does not have

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:45.639
that today. So this was good. I used that for a while, but then when I went to university

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:50.680
and tried to type mathematics, that wasn't so helpful. So eventually I switched to using

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:57.680
Tech, as in not LaTeX, Tech. I used that for a while until somebody said, hey, there's

00:02:01.239 --> 00:02:06.720
this other thing just come out called LaTeX, which has sort of better markup facilities.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.639
So I switched to LaTeX, and I used that for a long time, many, many years. It was fantastic.

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:17.080
Could write beautiful documents. I wrote several theses using LaTeX, lots and lots of reports

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:23.759
for clients, academic papers, and so on. So that was for the writing side, and then, of

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:29.919
course, I was doing data analysis. I'm a statistician, so I needed something for the statistical side,

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:36.559
and around 1987, I discovered this new tool. Well, it was new to me. It was before the

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:43.559
days of R, before the days of S+. It was an early version of S, running in a new IDE

00:02:45.759 --> 00:02:50.880
that went bust in about a year, but it was called Ace, and that was pretty cool. So I

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:57.880
was using S for a few years to do my statistical computing and using LaTeX to do the writing.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:02.199
So I haven't got a screenshot of S. I couldn't find one, but those of you who grew up knowing

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:09.080
S will see, recognise some of those books. Then eventually S+, came out, and so S+, had

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:16.080
quite a neat IDE. So S+, for the computing, LaTeX for the writing. It was pretty good,

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:20.600
actually. You could do quite a lot, except that, of course, you needed to keep these

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:25.919
things in sync, and I would be writing S++ code, generating graphics, saving them as

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:31.440
PostScript graphics, pulling them into my LaTeX documents, and if I changed the S++

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:35.679
code, I'd then have to re-run the LaTeX document to make sure it was up to date.

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:41.679
And so I developed this way of doing that, using... I switched to R at some point, too,

00:03:41.679 --> 00:03:48.679
yeah, about 2000, switched to R. That was the R website at around the year 2000. Hasn't

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:55.839
changed very much, has it? But the only thing that's different here is it says down the

00:03:56.039 --> 00:04:02.360
bottom... Where is it? It says somewhere it has some sort of... Oh, here it is. Web pages

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.800
currently under construction. That was there for a few years.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:11.800
Okay, so I invented this way of trying to make these things work together. So a make

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:18.660
file is a thing used by programmers to compile programs, and so you make a small change in

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:24.079
some function, you don't want to recompile everything. So you can use that in other tools

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:30.200
as well. So I was using it for R and LaTeX. If I made a change in my R file, it would

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:34.959
recompile the graphics. If I made a change in the LaTeX file, it would recompile the

00:04:34.959 --> 00:04:39.200
LaTeX. But it was smart enough to notice that if the graphics had changed and it needed

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:46.040
to recompile the LaTeX, even if the LaTeX file hadn't changed, and I wrote these sort

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:50.440
of complicated make files to do this. I thought this was super cool. I thought everyone would

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:56.920
do this. I would change the way everyone did R and LaTeX together. I wrote blog posts

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:04.519
about it, and I tweeted about it. Here's a tweet about it. Got one like, so you know

00:05:04.519 --> 00:05:17.160
I had a following. This was 2012. But this guy from the U.S. called Ewa noticed and he

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:21.959
tweeted back saying, or another way of separating R from reports and a little link to a thing

00:05:21.959 --> 00:05:26.679
he was developing called NitR. And I looked down and said, yeah, I know, but I reckon

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:33.480
my way is simpler. Does NitR have any real advantages over my approach with make files?

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:41.600
So I persisted on for a while and sort of kept an eye on what Ewa was doing. And after

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.559
a while I realized that, you know, he was right. And that although make files are useful

00:05:47.559 --> 00:05:51.720
for a lot of things, putting the R code and the LaTeX stuff together was going to make

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:57.519
a lot more sense. And so I switched and I started trying to write my academic papers

00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:03.160
using R Markdown, but of course they had to have a certain look, so then I ended up writing

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:09.959
R Markdown templates. That's a recent paper I wrote in an R Markdown template, and I was

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:15.559
writing client reports, so I had to write an R Markdown template for clients. And this

00:06:15.559 --> 00:06:22.359
was life changing. Like, this made my life so much easier. I was writing papers and writing

00:06:22.359 --> 00:06:28.600
reports, just had to have a couple of templates and everything was good. So I put those things

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:33.899
together and I couldn't think of a decent name for my package, so I called it Monash

00:06:33.899 --> 00:06:38.899
EBS templates, EBS being econometrics and business statistics, the department in which

00:06:38.899 --> 00:06:47.700
I work. And all you have to do is to use the template and you can generate these nice things.

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:53.940
And there's, before I show you that, there's lots of stuff that goes into the front end

00:06:53.940 --> 00:06:59.000
of an academic paper, so we need a title, we need a list of authors and where they come

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:04.480
from, their addresses, the abstract, key words, what number of working paper it is

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.559
in my department. They always want you to stick JEL codes on things and so on. So I

00:07:08.559 --> 00:07:15.799
just put all this stuff into the YAML and I can generate working papers. I convinced

00:07:15.799 --> 00:07:21.079
some other people in the department that this was the way to go. So if I put this in my

00:07:21.079 --> 00:07:25.959
YAML and it generates this beautiful front page and then the title page and then away

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.440
we go with the report.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:34.119
So that was sort of my first attempt at writing an R Markdown template and as I said it changed

00:07:34.119 --> 00:07:38.119
my life and then I thought well what else, I do a lot of other writing, maybe R Markdown

00:07:38.119 --> 00:07:45.119
can be used for other things. So at around the same time as this LaTeX S Plus thing,

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:52.600
I also got into making websites. The web was developed in 1993 I think, it took about four

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:59.640
months before I had a website and it looked a little bit like that. That was in 1997,

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:04.200
four years later, but it didn't change that much in the first four years. Some academics

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:10.600
still have websites that look like that. Mine evolved over time so eventually it looked

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:15.480
like that. This is handcrafted HTML because there was no other way to make websites. You

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:22.480
put it in a text editor, you wrote HTML code and then it looked like that.

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:28.200
Somewhere here, S Plus functions for time series, that became the forecast package for

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:35.200
R eventually, but the functions were originally on my website. Still handwriting HTML code,

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:45.840
just getting better at it. Still more hand crafting of HTML code. At this point I thought

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:52.960
I should have my own domain name and so I bought one, which is the one on the screen

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:59.559
there. Don't go there. I changed my domain name to something else with a dot com on the

00:08:59.559 --> 00:09:04.159
end eventually. Didn't worry about the old domain name, but because there were links

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:11.039
to it all over the web from all of my papers, a unpleasant organisation got it and has bad

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:15.119
stuff on there, so don't go there.

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:22.119
Then I thought handwriting HTML code is no fun. There's these new things for content

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:29.200
management systems, so I switched to one called Joomla. That was painful. I switched to another

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:35.960
one called WordPress, which was a little better, but slow. I was trying to write blog posts

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:40.520
about R and every time I would put my R code in, it would sort of strip out everything

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:45.880
after the less than hyphen, thinking that this is an HTML tag, and then I'd have to

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:50.760
go back in and sort of try to copy and paste my thing back in, and I was ending up spending

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:56.719
about as much time sort of trying to put all my stuff into the blog post as actually writing

00:09:56.719 --> 00:10:01.080
the code, so that was no fun. At this stage I switched to this URL. You're allowed to

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:07.159
go to that URL. That's the current one.

00:10:07.159 --> 00:10:14.159
That's the theme for WordPress, and then I thought, so this brings me to about 2016,

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:21.760
and Ewa wrote Blogdown, so I thought, okay, I use R Markdown for everything else from

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:29.080
all my other writing. Let's see if I can make a website using this thing called Blogdown.

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:33.880
You need a theme. I looked around the place. I figured out that Blogdown is built on Hugo.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:38.520
Kieran Healy had a great theme. He had his website on Hugo, so I forked his website,

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:44.119
deleted his content, stuck my website, my content in. With permission, he says in his

00:10:44.119 --> 00:10:48.919
GitHub repo that you're allowed to do that. Thank you, Kieran. Did all this on a very

00:10:48.919 --> 00:10:54.320
long flight between Melbourne and Amsterdam, copying and pasting and making sure everything

00:10:54.320 --> 00:11:01.039
worked, and then thought, great, now let's do the R bit, and it didn't work. Unfortunately,

00:11:01.039 --> 00:11:05.960
Kieran's theme didn't work with Blogdown. Not every Hugo theme works with Blogdown,

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:12.960
so flight home again. I start again. This time, I found another theme, and then I adapted

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:21.239
it to look like Kieran's because I still liked his website, so my own Blogdown theme that's

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:28.000
on that GitHub repo, and it's saved so much time doing a website that way.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:33.880
Okay, so another thing I was doing was writing books. My first book published in the late

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:40.880
90s was this one. It was, by textbook standards, an extremely successful book, but I didn't

00:11:42.119 --> 00:11:45.440
make any money out of it because the publisher makes a great deal of money and they didn't

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:51.200
give much to the authors, and I decided that I would never, ever do another book with a

00:11:51.239 --> 00:11:58.239
commercial publisher again because they screwed my students and didn't benefit me. So I thought

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:03.039
if I'm going to do another book, I'm going to put it online for free because my students

00:12:03.039 --> 00:12:06.700
wouldn't buy it. It was too expensive for the students to buy, so they would be looking

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:12.000
around on dodgy websites, getting bad information about forecasting, and using that instead

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.239
of the book that I thought was reasonably good. So I thought, let's do it online for

00:12:16.359 --> 00:12:23.039
free. This was before Bookdown existed. I didn't know anything. I mean, I knew I hadn't

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:27.239
thought about it as far as I know, so I thought, let's put it on. I can do it. This was also

00:12:27.239 --> 00:12:33.919
before my website was on Blogdown. So I tried to make it in WordPress. The first version

00:12:33.919 --> 00:12:40.159
of it came out in WordPress. I decided that wasn't so good, so I switched and I just copied

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:44.559
everything over to Drupal and a long, painful experience. That worked better. The first

00:12:44.559 --> 00:12:50.359
edition of the book came out in Drupal, but then I saw Bookdown and I thought, that's

00:12:50.359 --> 00:12:55.760
what I wanted, but it's just a few years too late. So the second edition of the book I

00:12:55.760 --> 00:13:02.760
did in Bookdown, and that meant that I could have a PDF version and an online version and

00:13:03.239 --> 00:13:07.840
everything would work beautifully, and it really did make an enormous difference.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:14.200
So that's the book as it is now. That's the online version. It's a relatively simple CSS

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:18.559
styling, but it's just running Bookdown. The LaTeX is more complicated because I wanted

00:13:18.559 --> 00:13:23.080
the LaTeX to look a certain way. That's a page from the LaTeX version, which is sold

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:24.080
on Amazon.

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:29.479
Okay, at this point, I was getting right into R Markdown. I'd made websites, I'd written

00:13:29.479 --> 00:13:35.400
books, and I had templates to do things. What about the slides that I used for talks? So

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:40.000
way back in the day, my slides looked like that using the LaTeX seminar package, and

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.200
then after a while, I switched to a package called Prosper, which gave nicer looking

00:13:44.200 --> 00:13:49.359
slides, and then I switched to Beamer, which was a little easier in some ways to do things,

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:54.919
and then I switched to R Markdown, and that is my slides that I use these days.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:14:01.919
So that's a package called BIMB. BIMB stands for BIMB is not Beamer, and it generates Beamer

