00:20:10.260 --> 00:20:14.839
and away it goes.

00:20:14.839 --> 00:20:18.699
So I'd just like to finally just say thank you to Yiwei. You really did make my life

00:20:18.699 --> 00:20:22.579
so much easier. I'm sorry I didn't believe you when you first said, have you looked at

00:20:22.579 --> 00:20:29.579
me like that? But you were right and I was wrong. Thank you for that.

00:20:37.619 --> 00:20:41.939
So the slides for this talk and all the links to packages and links to anything else that

00:20:41.939 --> 00:20:46.939
I've mentioned are going to be on that if you just go to that link there. Thank you.

00:20:47.939 --> 00:20:54.939
We have time for just a few questions, but I'll be sure to share all these with you.

00:20:57.219 --> 00:21:03.660
Any advice on converting awful Word template to beautiful R Markdown templates?

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:08.540
That's actually really hard. I look at the Word template and I copy and paste the text

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:13.780
and then I just start from scratch. I don't try to do anything in the Word styling itself.

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:20.780
I just start again because I find the Word templating is too difficult to convert.

00:21:22.979 --> 00:21:27.380
Which aspects of building templates or related YAML that are particularly challenging or

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:33.660
error prone? What advice would you give to a novice in this area?

00:21:33.660 --> 00:21:38.819
Almost all of the templating I've done has been with PDFs, so it's LaTeX and the backend.

00:21:38.819 --> 00:21:42.540
So you do have to be quite good at knowing about LaTeX, but I'd been using it for 20

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:47.060
years, so that was not a problem. But writing a PDF template, you have to know a reasonable

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:53.540
amount of LaTeX to know how to do that. I have less experience at writing HTML templates

00:21:53.540 --> 00:22:00.540
and no experience at all of writing Word templates, so I wouldn't even know how to do that.

00:22:01.140 --> 00:22:06.140
Someone else asked, do you use Bootstrap or other frameworks to style your templates?

00:22:06.459 --> 00:22:07.140
No.

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:14.140
And this is getting a few upvotes here. I like R Markdown, but I find Google Docs much

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:20.739
easier for collaboration and iteration with others. Any thoughts on that?

00:22:20.739 --> 00:22:26.260
So Google Docs are fine as long as you don't have a lot of R to do, but putting in R graphics

00:22:26.260 --> 00:22:33.099
inside a Google Doc, there's cutting and pasting to happen there, so that's painful. So I find

00:22:33.099 --> 00:22:38.140
R Markdown works much, much better if you've got any real statistical computing happening.

00:22:38.140 --> 00:22:45.140
And for collaboration purposes, I generally try and teach my collaborators how to use

00:22:45.939 --> 00:22:52.939
GitHub, and mostly that works okay. Occasionally I'm working with people that don't know GitHub

00:22:54.099 --> 00:23:00.300
or are not prepared to learn to use it, and then it's a little painful. There's lots

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:06.020
of emails and, can you please change this section, here's the words I want to add in,

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:08.780
and things like that.

00:23:08.780 --> 00:23:11.780
Thank you very much, Rob.

